<h2>Kansas Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Kansas offers several attractive incentives for solar and HVAC installations, with the federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) providing the most significant benefit. The 30% federal tax credit applies to the total cost of solar installations, including equipment, installation, and associated electrical work. This credit can be claimed dollar-for-dollar against federal income taxes owed, with unused portions carrying forward to future tax years. For a typical \$20,000 solar installation, this credit provides \$6,000 in tax savings.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal 30% Solar Tax Credit:</strong> Available through 2032, this credit covers 30% of total solar system costs including equipment, installation, permits, and interconnection fees. The credit applies to both residential and commercial installations and can be combined with other incentives. No maximum limit exists on the credit amount, making it valuable for larger installations.</li>
<li><strong>Kansas Property Tax Exemption:</strong> Solar energy systems are exempt from property tax assessments in Kansas, meaning the added home value from solar installations won't increase property tax bills. This exemption saves homeowners \$200-500 annually on property taxes for typical residential systems.</li>
<li><strong>Evergy Solar Rebates:</strong> Evergy offers rebates up to \$2,500 for residential solar installations, with specific requirements for system size and installer certification. Additional rebates are available for energy storage systems and smart inverters that provide grid support services.</li>
<li><strong>HVAC Rebates and Programs:</strong> Evergy provides rebates for high-efficiency HVAC equipment including \$300-800 for ENERGY STAR qualified heat pumps and air conditioners, \$100-300 for smart thermostats, and additional incentives for duct sealing and insulation improvements.</li>
<li><strong>Net Metering:</strong> Kansas utilities offer net metering programs crediting excess solar production at retail rates, maximizing the value of solar generation. Unused credits typically roll over monthly with annual true-up provisions.</li>
</ul>

